Being generic seems to be the Walsh way. The references are over-familiar, the revelations about living alone in a grim basement flat in London – the hour’s big theme - are under-remarkable. The best bits come when he shifts the focus away from his yawn-inducing slacker lifestyle, with its constant trips to the 24-hour off-licence over the road, and simply inhabits the bric-a-brac of his strangely empty existence. He does a nice spoof advert for an iPhone, itemising its frustrations. And he expertly impersonates the stand-up comedians he catches on TV (his Michael McIntyre, self-defeatingly, unleashes levels of laughter not heard elsewhere). Sound thin? It is.
